    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-19T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-19T13:00:00-05:00" n="422"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d422">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4318: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain (<persName corresp="#p_AR1"
                            type="from">Atherton</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-19T18:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 19, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 19—2:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>77. Foreign Office sent for me this evening to inform me of a cable just received
                    from <persName corresp="#p_LSMW1">Lampson</persName> that in view of the danger
                    to property and lives from shell fire in Settlement British Minister had “on his
                    own initiative” joined with his American and other colleagues in representations
                    to Chinese and Japanese authorities at Shanghai reserving all rights in claim to
                    damages caused inadvertently or otherwise by their respective military
                    operations.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_VSRG1">Vansittart</persName> informed me immediately on
                    receipt of this cable Foreign Office telegraphed <persName corresp="#p_LSMW1"
                        >Lampson</persName> approving his action and that <persName
                        corresp="#p_SSJ1">Sir John Simon</persName> was anxious you should know at
                    once of this Anglo-American cooperation under approval of the Foreign Office,
                    which so nearly coincided with the draft declaration referred to in your 62,
                    February 15, 6 p.m. <persName corresp="#p_VSRG1">Vansittart</persName> pointed
                    out draft declaration was only addressed to the Japanese, and as he had stated
                    to me on Tuesday last was not considered opportune.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
